        • [ - ] kirton - member since 09-Feb-15

          @What4 As I understand, players start at a rating of 6 and increase for every good interaction (touches, completed passes, key passes, completed dribbles, shots on target) and is reduced for bad plays (missed passes, losing the ball, unsuccessful tackles etc.). Players that get subbed off (especially midfielders who haven't scored or assisted) tend to get a lower score because of the gradual way they build their rating. Iniesta would have had more time to make successful passes etc. I always try to remember that the score can't capture off the ball play, like movement to draw a player out of position or pressuring the ball without attempting to tackle. Nor do they account for the quality, 10 amazing first touches and great passes that lead no where will be rated less than 50 basic trap and pass plays.
